It was found that the anodic ECL intensity of the Au NCs@GQDs modified electrode obviously decreased when the pentoxifylline was added into the electrolyte (Fig. 6
                        A). It showed that the pentoxifylline can quench the ECL of Au NCs@GQDs. It has been reported that there was no oxidation peak of pentoxifylline that can be observed when the pH value of electrolyte was beyond 7.0 [10]. In this work, the ECL detection was conducted in ca. pH 11.5 electrolyte solution [26], so the reason of ECL decrease here may be that the oxidation reaction of pentoxifylline absorbed on the surface of Au NCs@GQDs electrode could not occur, hindering the charge transfer between TEA and Au NCs@GQDs. At the same time, the decreased ECL intensity (ΔI) was linear with the increasing concentration of pentoxifylline ranging from 7.0 × 10−7 to 1.2 × 10-4 mol/L (R = 0.9995) with the detection limit of 9.0 × 10-8 mol/L (S/N = 3) (Fig. 6B). The ECL detection method showed a wider linearity range and a lower limit of detection comparing with conventional chromatography, spectroscopy and electrochemical technique (Table 1
                        ).
